    <div class="secondarytitle">
      <h2>When You Hit The Wall</h2>
        <span class="stacked">
            <img class="righted" src="<%= asset_path 'the_wall.png' %>" width="350" height="223" style="padding: 5px 0px 15px 15px;" alt="the wall of resistance" />
            <p>A few weeks ago I hit a wall. Work was going great until someone told me, "it can't be done." How many times has an <em>expert</em> said this about an envisioned technology? Frustration followed. Spit. Angry shouts. 20 pushups.</p>
            <p>If you've ever endeavoured to change, to improve, to create, or otherwise make a difference, you have met The Wall. Change always comes with resistance. The most difficult seems to come from other people and from ourselves. From other people because it's easy to take rebuffs personally. From ourselves because pride keeps us from admitting we need to be different; we're reluctant to lose things and habits which make us feel good or right.</p>
            <p>An agent of change gets resistance from other people. Why? Because the agent looks like the wall. So don't be surprised when they get angry or don't understand. Don't take it personally. It's not right. When we take it personally, we focus on the person instead of the problem. I like to get a moment of silence to remember that I must be the change, work smarter, and sometimes harder.</p>
            <iframe class="righted" src="http://rcm.amazon.com/e/cm?lt1=_blank&bc1=FFFFFF&IS2=1&npa=1&bg1=FFFFFF&fc1=000000&lc1=3E3EFF&t=comfdesi-20&o=1&p=8&l=as1&m=amazon&f=ifr&ref=tf_til&asins=1936719010" style="width:120px;height:200px;" scrolling="no" marginwidth="0" marginheight="0" frameborder="0"></iframe> 
            <p>There's only one solution to personal change that works 100% of the time for me. "Do the Work!" This was the title of a book recently authored by Steven Pressfield and recommend to me by a Silicon Valley billionaire. Here's a valuable lesson: Resistance will tell you anything you want to hear to convince you not to take action. Ignore it. Follow through. Do it now. Now!</p>
            <p>A good friend once explained the options for facing The Wall. Hop over it. Dig under it. Walk around it. (my favorite) Go through it. Stay there. Or turn around. I like the way that gets me to success. The experts are often wrong. Made it over this time.</p>
            <p class="righted">12/25/12</p>
        </span>
    </div>

